unded in the same kinds of physical and emotional experiences that performers are necessarily concerned to project. Analysis and performance are thus deeply compatible and can enjoy an equitable, fruitful relationship. The first three chapters theorize this stance; thelast three apply it to works by Chopin, Beethoven, and Schumann, respectively. Jeffrey Swinkin is assistant professor of music theory at the University of Oklahoma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxInterpretation (Phrasing, dynamics, etc.). 0aMusicxPerformancexPsychological aspects. 0aMusical analysis. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Instruction & Study / Theory.2bisacsh  aBeethoven.  aChopin.  aSchenkerian analysis.  aSchumann.  amusic studies.  amusic theory.  amusicology.  aperformance studies.  atheory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782046998?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046998/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles